A/B Testing¶

The Cookie Cats dataset used in this A/B test is from Kaggle. It is a dataset for a mobile game with the following fields:

  • userid: A unique identifier for each player.
  • version: Indicates whether the player was assigned the game with level 1 at Gate 30 or Gate 40
  • sum_gamerounds: Number of rounds played in the first week after installation.
  • retention_1: Binary variable on whether the player returned to play one day after installing.
  • retention_7: Binary variable on whether the player returned to play seven days after installing.

A/B Test Setup¶

Question: Does shifting the placement of the first gate from Gate 30 to Gate 40 impact player retention?

Hypothesis:

  • H0: Proportions of retention after day 1 and day 7 are equal for Gate 30 and Gate 40 players.
  • H1: Proportions of retention after day 1 and day 7 are different between Gate 30 and Gate 40 players.

Groups:

  • Control group: Gate 30 players
  • Treatment group: Gate 40 players

Metrics:

  • Player retention after 1 day
  • Player retention after 7 days

# Function to create bar plot
def bar_plot_series(series, xlabel, ylabel, title):
    plt.figure(figsize=(4, 3))
    ax = series.plot(kind='bar')

    for i, value in enumerate(series):
        ax.text(i, value + value * 0.01, f'{value:,.0f}', ha='center', va='bottom', fontsize=10)

    plt.xlabel(xlabel)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel)
    plt.title(title)
    plt.xticks(rotation=0)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

n_users = df.userid.nunique()

gate_30_data = df[df["version"]=="gate_30"]
gate_40_data = df[df["version"]=="gate_40"]

stages = ["Downloads", "1-Round Player", "1-day Retention", "7-day Retention"]

values_30 = [gate_30_data.userid.nunique(), # num of game_30 users
             gate_30_data[gate_30_data["sum_gamerounds"]>0].userid.nunique(), # game_30 users played 1+ round
             gate_30_data.retention_1.sum(), # came back after 1 day
             gate_30_data.retention_7.sum()] # came back after 7 days

percentage_30 = [str(round(values_30[i]/n_users*100, 1)) + "% of all users" + "<br>"
                 + str(round(values_30[i]/gate_30_data.userid.nunique()*100, 1)) + "% of group" for i in range(len(values_30))]

values_30 = pd.DataFrame(dict(number=values_30, stage=stages, percentage=percentage_30))
values_30["group"] = "gate_30"

values_40 = [gate_40_data.userid.nunique(), gate_40_data[gate_40_data["sum_gamerounds"]>0].userid.nunique(),
             gate_40_data.retention_1.sum(), gate_40_data.retention_7.sum()]

percentage_40 = [str(round(values_40[i]/n_users*100, 1)) + "% of all users" + "<br>"
                 + str(round(values_40[i]/gate_40_data.userid.nunique()*100, 1)) + "% of group" for i in range(len(values_40))]
values_40 = pd.DataFrame(dict(number=values_40, stage=stages, percentage=percentage_40))
values_40["group"] = "gate_40"

funnel_data = pd.concat([values_30, values_40], axis=0)
display(funnel_data)

fig = px.funnel(funnel_data, x='number', y='stage', color='group', text="percentage", title="Game Conversion")

Power Analysis¶

In [16]:
power = 0.8
alpha = 0.05
d = 0.1 # desired effect size (difference between proportions of retention for Gates 30 & 40)
proportion_30_ret1 = 0.5 + d/2
proportion_40_ret1 = 0.5 - d/2

effect_size = proportion_effectsize(proportion_30_ret1, proportion_40_ret1)

analysis = NormalIndPower()
sample_size = analysis.solve_power(effect_size=effect_size, alpha=alpha, power=power, alternative='two-sided')

print(f"Required sample size for Group A: {sample_size:.0f}")
print(f"Required sample size for Group B: {sample_size:.0f}")

Required sample size for Group A: 391
Required sample size for Group B: 391

Bootstrap Sampling¶

In [17]:
# Conduct bootstrap sampling
def bootstrap_sampling(data, n_samples=10000, sample_size=None):
    if sample_size is None:
        sample_size = len(data)
    bootstrap_samples = np.zeros(n_samples) # array to store bootstrap samples
    for i in range(n_samples):
        bootstrap_sample = np.random.choice(data, size=sample_size, replace=True)
        bootstrap_samples[i] = np.mean(bootstrap_sample)
    return bootstrap_samples

bs_30_ret1 = bootstrap_sampling(gate_30_data['retention_1'])
bs_30_ret7 = bootstrap_sampling(gate_30_data['retention_7'])
bs_40_ret1 = bootstrap_sampling(gate_40_data['retention_1'])
bs_40_ret7 = bootstrap_sampling(gate_40_data['retention_7'])

bs_mean_30_1 = np.mean(bs_30_ret1)
bs_mean_30_7 = np.mean(bs_30_ret7)
bs_mean_40_1 = np.mean(bs_40_ret1)
bs_mean_40_7 = np.mean(bs_40_ret7)

confidence_level = 1 - alpha
lower_ci_30_1, upper_ci_30_1 = np.quantile(bs_30_ret1, [(1-confidence_level)/2, 1 - (1-confidence_level)/2])
lower_ci_40_1, upper_ci_40_1 = np.quantile(bs_40_ret1, [(1-confidence_level)/2, 1 - (1-confidence_level)/2])
lower_ci_30_7, upper_ci_30_7 = np.quantile(bs_30_ret7, [(1-confidence_level)/2, 1 - (1-confidence_level)/2])
lower_ci_40_7, upper_ci_40_7 = np.quantile(bs_40_ret7, [(1-confidence_level)/2, 1 - (1-confidence_level)/2])

print("Gate 30, 1-day Retention:")
print(f"Bootstrap Mean: {bs_mean_30_1:.2f}")
print(f"{int(confidence_level*100)}% Confidence Interval: ({lower_ci_30_1:.2f}, {upper_ci_30_1:.2f})")
print()
print("Gate 40, 1-day Retention:")
print(f"Bootstrap Mean: {bs_mean_40_1:.2f}")
print(f"{int(confidence_level*100)}% Confidence Interval: ({lower_ci_40_1:.2f}, {upper_ci_40_1:.2f})")
print()
print("Gate 30, 7-day Retention:")
print(f"Bootstrap Mean: {bs_mean_30_7:.2f}")
print(f"{int(confidence_level*100)}% Confidence Interval: ({lower_ci_30_7:.2f}, {upper_ci_30_7:.2f})")
print()
print("Gate 40, 7-day Retention:")
print(f"Bootstrap Mean: {bs_mean_40_7:.2f}")
print(f"{int(confidence_level*100)}% Confidence Interval: ({lower_ci_40_7:.2f}, {upper_ci_40_7:.2f})")

Hypothesis Testing Results¶

In [19]:
# Calculate difference between groups
bs_ret1_diff = bs_30_ret1 - bs_40_ret1
bs_ret7_diff = bs_30_ret7 - bs_40_ret7

# H0: Gate 30 and 40 have no difference (d=0)
# H1: Gate 30 and 30 are different (d!=0)
low_ci1, high_ci1 = np.quantile(bs_ret1_diff, [(1-confidence_level)/2, 1 - (1-confidence_level)/2])
low_ci7, high_ci7 = np.quantile(bs_ret7_diff, [(1-confidence_level)/2, 1 - (1-confidence_level)/2])

# Calculate observed difference
mean_diff_ret1 = np.mean(bs_ret1_diff)
print(f"Observed difference between Gate 30 & 40 1-day Retention: {round(mean_diff_ret1*100,3)}%")
mean_diff_ret7 = np.mean(bs_ret7_diff)
print(f"Observed difference between Gate 30 & 40 7-day Retention: {round(mean_diff_ret7*100,3)}%")

Observed difference between Gate 30 & 40 1-day Retention: 0.591%
Observed difference between Gate 30 & 40 7-day Retention: 0.821%
In [24]:
# Calculate p-value - the proportion of bootstrap differences that are as or more extreme than the observed difference
p_value_ret1 = np.mean(bs_ret1_diff <= 0) + np.mean(bs_ret1_diff >= high_ci1-(0-low_ci1))

print(f"P-value 1-day Retention: {p_value_ret1}")
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))

sns.histplot(bs_ret1_diff, bins=100, kde=True)

plt.axvline(mean_diff_ret1, color='blue', linestyle='solid', linewidth=1)
plt.axvline(high_ci1, color='blue', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)
plt.axvline(low_ci1, color='blue', linestyle='dashed', linewidth=1)

# Adding text labels for the lines
plt.text(mean_diff_ret1, plt.ylim()[1]*.95, f'Mean: {mean_diff_ret1*100:.2f}%', ha='center')
plt.text(high_ci1, plt.ylim()[1]*0.8, f'Upper CI: {high_ci1*100:.2f}%', ha='center')
plt.text(low_ci1, plt.ylim()[1]*0.8, f'Lower CI: {low_ci1*100:.2f}%', ha='center')

plt.title('1-day Retention Difference between Gate 30 and Gate 40')
plt.xlabel('Observed Difference')
plt.ylabel('Frequency')
plt.show()

P-value 1-day Retention: 0.0757

The p-value is greater than alpha. Also, 0 is in the confidence interval. There is not enough evidence to reject the null hypothesis for 1-day retention. There is no difference in 1-day retention if the gate is at 30 or 40.

There is a difference in 7-day retention between Gates 30 and 40 (0 is not in the confidence interval, and the p-value is less than alpha). Moving the gate from 30 to 40 decreases 7-day retention by 0.82%.

Conclusion¶

It is not a good idea to move the gate from 30 to 40 because doing so decreases 7-day retention and has no impact on 1-day retention.

Further analysis should evaluate if there are other variables that impact retention, such as the number of rounds played.
